<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[701,1228,1202,1759]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
ETYMOLOGY: The specific name is a patronym in honor of Elicio Tapia, collector of the only known specimens, in recognition of his tremendous contributions to the success of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Expedition." authorityName="Expedition." box="[871,1122,1500,1522]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Niarchos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Niarchos Expedition.</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[701,1228,1202,1759]" lastBlockId="29.[93,620,213,1036]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
DIAGNOSIS: This species is clearly most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Platnick &amp; Duperre" authorityYear="2010" box="[911,1016,1559,1582]" class="Arachnida" family="Oonopidae" genus="Niarchos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elicioi">
<emphasis box="[911,1016,1559,1582]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">N. elicioi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing with it a greatly narrowed anterior projection on the male endites, a tiny retroventral projection on the male palpal bulb, and a hypertrophied embolar region, but can easily be distinguished by the shorter embolar region (figs. 152–156) of males and the arched posterior margin of the epigastric sclerite (figs. 165, 166) of females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
